fields.json:
{
	"Anemia_Mortality_Inverse_Width": {"type":0, "default":20,  "min":0.1, "max":1000000, "help":"Range: 0.1 to 1e+06", "tooltip":"The inverse width relative to threshold value of mortality turn-on around threshold for anemia.", "label":"Anemia Mortality Inverse Width"},
	"Anemia_Mortality_Threshold": {"type":0, "default":3, "min":0, "max":100, "tooltip":"The threshold value on hemoglobin count in grams per deciliter (g/dL) at which 50% of individuals die per day.", "help":"Range: 0 to 100"},
	"Anemia_Severe_Inverse_Width": {"type":0, "default":20, "min":0,  "max":1000000, "tooltip":"The inverse width relative to threshold value of severe disease turn-on around threshold for anemia.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1,000,000"},
	"Anemia_Severe_Threshold": {"type":0, "default":5, "min":0, "max":100, "tooltip":"The severe disease threshold level for anemia. Threshold units are in grams per deciliter (g/dL).", "help":"Range: 10 to 100"},
	"Antibody_Capacity_Growth_Rate": {"type":0, "default":0.1, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"Maximum daily rate of specific antibody capacity increase. Antibody production begins at capacity of 0.3. Hyperimmunity results at 0.4. The actual growth rate will tend to be lower and is a function of antigen concentrations.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Antibody_CSP_Decay_Days": {"type":0, "default":90, "min":1, "max":3.40282e+038, "tooltip":"Exponential decay time for CSP (Circumsporozoite Protein) antibody concentration (in days) when boosted above natural maximum concentration.", "help":"Range: 1 to 3.40282e+038"},
	"Antibody_CSP_Killing_Inverse_Width": {"type":0, "default":1.5, "min":1e-006, "max":1e+006, "tooltip":"Inverse width of sigmoidal sporozoite killing function of CSP antibody concentration.", "help":"Range: 1e-006 to 1e+006"},
	"Antibody_CSP_Killing_Threshold": {"type":0, "default":10, "min":1e-006, "max":1e+006, "tooltip":"Threshold value on CSP antibody concentration for sporozoite killing. ", "help":"Range: 1e-006 to 1e+006"},
	"Antibody_IRBC_Kill_Rate": {"type":0, "default":2, "min":0, "max":1000, "tooltip":"Factor multiplied by antibody level to produce the rate of clearance of the infected red blood cell (IRBC) population.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1,000"},
	"Antibody_Memory_Level": {"type":0, "default":0.2, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"Limiting level of antibody capacity that remains after a prolonged absence of a specific antigen. The antibody capacity decays to this level gradually after infection is cleared. The decay rate in antibody capacity is set so that hyperimmunity is lost within 4 months, and capacity continues to decay to this level. The antibody memory level is relevant for year-scale dynamics, but not for long dynamics (10-20 years).", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Antibody_Stimulation_C50": {"type":0, "default":10, "min":0.1, "max":10000, "tooltip":"Concentration of an antigen, measured in IRBC/ul at which growth in antibody capacity against the antigen increases at half the maximum rate specified by Antibody_Capacity_Growth_Rate.", "help":"Range: 0.1 to 10,000"},
	"Antigen_Switch_Rate": {"type":0, "default":2e-009, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"Antigenic switching rate per infected red blood cell per asexual cycle. See the Parasite_Switch_Type parameter for different switching patterns.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Base_Gametocyte_Fraction_Male": {"type":0, "default":0.2, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"Fraction of gametocytes that are male.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Base_Gametocyte_Mosquito_Survival_Rate": {"type":0, "default":0.01, "min":0, "max":10000, "tooltip":"Average fraction of gametocytes in blood meal that are successful in infecting mosquito in the absence of other modulating effects, such as fever.", "help":"Range: 0 to 10,000", "label":"Base Gametocyte Surviva Rate"},
	"Base_Gametocyte_Production_Rate": {"type":0, "default":0.02, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"Fraction of IRBCs producing gametocytes.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Base_Sporozoite_Survival_Fraction": {"type":0, "default":0.25, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"Fraction of sporozoites that survive to infect a hepatocyte in the absence of anti-CSP protection.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Clinical_Fever_Threshold_High": {"type":0, "default":1, "min":0, "max":15, "tooltip":"The fever threshold (in degrees Celsius above normal) to start a clinical incident.", "help":"Range: 0 to 15"},
	"Clinical_Fever_Threshold_Low": {"type":0, "default":1, "min":0, "max":5, "tooltip":"The fever threshold (in degrees Celsius above normal) to end a clinical incident.", "help":"Range: 0 to 5"},
	"Cytokine_Gametocyte_Inactivation": {"type":0, "default":0.02, "min":0, "max":1, "tooltip":"The strength of inflammatory response inactivation of gametocytes.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1"},
	"Enable_Variable_Pyrogenic_Threshold": {"type":"bool", "default":0, "tooltip":"Check box to include heterogeneity among individuals in the strength of the innate immune activation at a given level of infection. Set to false (0) to indicate homogeneity among individuals, implying that they all have the threshold specified in the Pyrogenic_Threshold parameter.\n\nThe distribution used to represent heterogeneity is set in the demographics file for immunity modification. If a user selects uniform distribution, the two distribution parameters set the upper and lower limits. If a user selects normal distribution, the two parameters set mean and standard deviation.", "label":"Variable Pyrogenic Threshold"},
	"Falciparum_MSP_Variants": {"type":0, "default":100, "min":0, "max":100, "tooltip":"The number of distinct MSP variants for P. falciparum malaria in the overall parasite population in the simulation, not necessarily in an individual.", "help":"Range: 0 to 100"},
	"Falciparum_Nonspecific_Types": {"type":0, "default":20, "min":0, "max":100, "tooltip":"The number of distinct non-specific types of P. falciparum malaria.", "help":"Range: 0 to 100"},
	"Falciparum_PfEMP1_Variants": {"type":0, "default":1000, "min":0, "max":2.14748e+009, "tooltip":"The number of distinct PfEMP1 variants for P. falciparum malaria in the overall parasite population in the simulation.", "help":"Range: 0 to 2.14748e+009"},
	"Fever_Detection_Threshold": {"type":0, "default":1, "min":0.5, "max":5, "tooltip":"Level of body temperature above normal, in degrees Celsius, corresponding to detectable fever. Normal body temperature is defined as 37 degrees Celsius.", "help":"Range: 0.5 to 5"},
	"Fever_IRBC_Kill_Rate": {"type":0, "default":0.15, "min":0, "max":1000, "tooltip":"Factor multiplied by fever level to produce a decay rate of infected red blood cell population due to inflammatory innate immune response.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1,000"},
	"Fever_Mortality_Inverse_Width": {"type":0, "default":10, "min":0.1, "max":1e+006, "tooltip":"The inverse width relative to threshold value of mortality turn-on around threshold for fever.", "help":"Range: 0.1 to 1e+006"},
	"Fever_Mortality_Threshold": {"type":0, "default":3, "min":0, "max":1000, "tooltip":"The fever mortality threshold for a simulation in units of degrees Celsius above normal body temperature. Sets the midpoint in the sigmoidal response for mortality rate associated with fever.", "help":"Range: 0 to 1,000"},
	"Fever_Severe_Inverse_Width": {"type":0, "default":10, "min":0.1, "max":1e+006, "tooltip":"The inverse width relative to threshold value of severe disease turn-on around threshold for fever.", "help":"Range: 0.1 to 1e+006"},
	"Fever_Severe_Threshold": {"type":0, "default":1.5, "min":0, "max":10, "tooltip":"The severe disease threshold level for fever.", "help":"Range: 0 to 10"},
	"Gametocyte_Stage_Survival_Rate": {"type":0, "default":1, "min":0, "max":1, "help":"Range: 0 to 1", "tooltip":"Rate of gametocyte survival from one development stage to the next in the absence of drugs or inflammatory immune response."},
	"Malaria_Strain_Model": {"type":"choice", "default":"FALCIPARUM_NONRANDOM_STRAIN", "tooltip":"The generator that is used to construct the antigenic repertoire of a malaria infection.", "choices":["FALCIPARUM_NONRANDOM_STRAIN", "FALCIPARUM_RANDOM50_STRAIN", "FALCIPARUM_RANDOM_STRAIN", "FALCIPARUM_STRAIN_GENERATOR"]},
	"Max_MSP1_Antibody_Growthrate": {"type":0, "default":0.02, "min":0, "max":1, "help":"Range: 0 to 1", "tooltip":"Maximum increase in MSP1 antibody capacity during each asexual cycle. The higher this value, the sooner early clearances are observed and the earlier the parasite density envelope decreases."},
	"Max_MSP2_Antibody_Growthrate": {"type":0, "default":0.02, "min":0, "max":1000, "help":"Range: 0 to 1,000", "tooltip":"Maximum increase in MSP2 antibody capacity during each asexual cycle. Higher values lead to earlier clearances."},
	"Mean_Sporozoites_Per_Bite": {"type":0, "default":11, "min":0, "max":1000, "help":"Range: 0 to 1000", "tooltip":"Mean number of sporozoites per infectious mosquito bite."},
	"Merozoites_Per_Hepatocyte": {"type":0, "default":15000, "min":0, "max":3.40282e+038, "help":"Range: 0 to 3.40282e+038", "tooltip":"Number of merozoites released by a single infected schizont after each asexual cycle. The number of resulting IRBC's depends on the RBC availability and merozoite-specific immunity."},
	"Merozoites_Per_Schizont": {"type":0, "default":16, "min":0, "max":1000, "help":"Range: 0 to 1000", "tooltip":"Number of merozoites released by a single infected schizont after each asexual cycle. The number of resulting IRBC’s depends on the RBC availability and merozoite-specific immunity."},

	"Min_Adapted_Response": {"type":0, "default":0.02, "min":0, "max":1, "help":"Range: 0 to 1", "tooltip":"Minimum level of antibody stimulation to novel antigen. The value sets the low-range asymptote for antibody capacity growth, which is calculated from the Antibody_Capacity_Growthrate parameter and antigen density, in the presence of any nonzero antigen level."},
	"Min_Days_Between_Clinical_Incidents": {"type":0, "default":3, "min":0, "max":1e+006, "help":"Range: 0 to 1e+006", "tooltip":"The number of days with fever below the low threshold before a new incident can start when the high fever threshold is again exceeded."},
	"MSP1_Merozoite_Kill_Fraction": {"type":0, "default":0.5, "min":0, "max":1, "help":"Range: 0 to 1", "tooltip":"Fraction of merozoites inhibited from invading new erythrocytes when MSP1-specific antibody level is 1."},
	"MSP2_Merozoite_Kill_Fraction": {"type":0, "default":0.5, "min":0, "max":1, "help":"Range: 0 to 1", "tooltip":"Fraction of merozoites inhibited from invading new erythrocytes when MSP2-specific antibody level is 1."},

	"New_Diagnostic_Sensitivity": {"type":0, "default":0.01, "min":0.0001, "max":100000, "help":"Range: 0.0001 to 100000", "tooltip":"The number of microliters of blood tested to find single parasites in a new diagnostic (corresponds to inverse parasites/microliters sensitivity)."},
	"Nonspecific_Antibody_Growth_Rate_Factor": {"type":0, "default":0.5, "min":0, "max":1000, "help":"Range: 0 to 1,000", "tooltip":"Factor that adjusts Antibody_Capacity_Growth_Rate for the less immunogenic surface proteins called minor epitopes.", "label":"Nonspecific Antibody Growth Rate"},
	"Nonspecific_Antigenicity_Factor": {"type":0, "default":0.3, "min":0, "max":1, "help":"Range: 0 to 1", "tooltip":"Nonspecific antigenicity factor that adjusts antibody IRBC kill rate to account for IRBCs caused by antibody responses to antigenically weak surface proteins."},
	"Number_Of_Asexual_Cycles_Without_Gametocytes": {"type":0, "default":1, "min":0, "max":2.14748e+009, "help":"Range: 0 to 2.14748e+009", "tooltip":"Number of asexual reproduction cycles that do not produce gametocytes. "Vaccine_Type":  {"type": "choice", "choices": ["Generic", "TransmissionBlocking", "AcquisitionBlocking", "MortalityBlocking"], "tooltip": "Type of vaccine to distribute in a vaccine intervention. Possible values are:

fields.description: The following parameters provide a straightforward mechanism for modifying various key parameters by multiplicative scale factors. This can be especially useful for understanding the sensitivities of disease dynamics to input data without requiring modifications to demographics or migration files. For example, one might set x_Birth to a value less than 1 to simulate a lower future birth rate due to increased economic prosperity and available medical technology.
